The microwave treatment of TEPA, CA, and CuSO4 mixture produced a brown colored solid. The solid dissolved easily in water to form a homogeneous solution. The particles were distributed uniformly with a mean diameter of 5.16 nm, as obtained by Transmission Electron Microscopy (TEM) analysis (Fig. 1
                        ). The selected area diffraction (SAD) pattern revealed the amorphous nature of the particles (Fig. 1). X-ray Powder Diffraction (XRD) (Fig. 1) showed a broad peak around 21° 2θ, which corresponds to amorphous carbon [29]. On the other hand, no significant peaks for CuO or Cu2O were observed in the XRD pattern indicating amorphous nature [30]. X-ray photoelectron spectroscopy (XPS) revealed the presence of C1s, N1s, O1s, and Cu2p (Fig. 2
                        ). Further elemental analysis of C1s revealed peaks at 283.7 eV, 285.2 eV, 287.15 eV, and 287.7 eV for CC, C–C, CN, and CO bonds, respectively [31–33]. Deconvolution of N1s revealed peaks at 398.4 eV and 399.5 eV for pyridinic N and pyrrolic N, respectively [34]. An analysis of Cu2p showed peaks at 932.5 eV and 952.7 eV for Cu2p3/2 and Cu2p1/2, respectively along with few satellite peaks for Cu2+. In addition to the main peaks, few satellite peaks also appeared. This indicated an association of CuO along with CDC [35,36]. Fourier-transform infrared spectroscopy (FTIR) spectroscopy showed peaks at 800 cm−1, 1207 cm−1, 1660 cm−1, 1762 cm−1, 2879 cm−1, and 3434 cm−1. These peaks corresponded to aromatic bending of C–H, C–N, C–C benzene/CO amide, CO, C–H, and N–H, respectively [37] (Fig. 2). The zeta potential of CDC was measured to be +5.42 mV. The surface charge was attributed to surface functional groups and CuO.

Because dye aggregation is affected significantly by the presence of surfactants [42], a cationic surfactant, cetrimonium bromide (CTAB), and an anionic surfactant, sodium dodecyl sulfate (SDS), were introduced separately to the reaction medium. The aggregation in RhB caused strong coupling within the molecular dipoles, followed by a split in the excited energy levels with a doubly degenerate ground state in the dimer [42]. In aggregated forms, the position of the excited states (J-an H- bands) plays an important role. This would influence the FRET interactions of the CDC-RhB system in the presence of surfactants. Surfactant molecules form micelles in a solvent medium. Micelles modify electron transfer within the donor and acceptor through gated electron transfer [43]. On the other hand, this type of phenomenon is facilitated by the controllable interconversion rate and electron transfer rate as well as by the stable initial states of the donor-acceptor. The molecular electronics can be enlightened by the study of the electric field on the micellar surface [44]. Pal et al. [45] mentioned that within the organized assembly, the electron transfer process is hindered due to separation of the donor acceptor by the micellar layer. If, however, the donor-acceptor remained inside the surfactant boundary, energy transfer might be tuned due to modification of the distance between the donor-acceptor. In the present case, under surfactant confinement, energy transfer increased within the CDC and RhB system (Fig. 5
                        ). The quenching efficiency, ηq, was calculated to be 21.2% and 19.8%, respectively, at a RhB concentration of 0.105 mM in a CTAB and SDS medium. The increase in quenching was accompanied by improvement in the emission of the RhB at 584 nm. This indicates a significant FRET interaction between CDC and RhB within confinement. The higher ηq value in CTAB than in SDS could be explained by the molecular interactions depending on the size of the host. CTAB (C16 chain) being larger in size than SDS (C12 chain), can accommodate larger numbers of molecules within the micellar periphery. The quenching efficiency was also calculated in terms of the lifetime. An analysis of fluorescence decay (Fig. 6
                        ) showed a continuous decrease in the lifetime of the CDC-RhB system within the confinement with increasing RhB concentration (documented in Table S1). The lifetimes were calculated to be 11.7 ns and 9.96 ns for the CDC-RhB/CTAB and CDC-RhB/SDS systems, respectively, at a RhB concentration of 0.105 mM. CDC/CTAB and CDC/SDS solutions with lifetimes of 13.35 ns and 11.70 ns, respectively, were taken as the control solutions, and the FRET efficiency was calculated using equation (1). This shows that for CDC-RhB/CTAB and CDC-RhB/SDS systems, ηFRET were 12.35% and 14.7%, respectively. This does not agree with the quenching efficiencies obtained from the fluorescence intensity values. The lifetimes did not follow the fluorescence intensity trends. On the other hand, the difference was not very high. Under confinement, in addition to accommodating the number of molecules, the electrostatic interaction between the host and guest also plays an important role. CTAB and SDS, being cationic and anionic surfactants, have different behaviors. As CDC contains both electron donating and withdrawing functional groups (CO, N–H), the charge on RhB might play a pivotal role. RhB, being a cationic dye, prefers the electrostatically suitable environment of SDS. Further experimentation showed that the nature and concentration of the surfactant plays an important role in FRET (Fig. S4). Variations of the concentration of both the surfactants within a range of 0.9 μM-0.012 M showed that the medium maximum FRET efficiency was observed at 5 mM surfactants, irrespective of the surfactant. Therefore, further experiments were carried out at a 5 mM surfactant concentration.
